........................................................................................................................................................................... 2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,885,1900]" box="[151,1435,917,940]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyLead box="[151,1435,917,940]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">- Male ............................................................................................................................................................................ 6</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,885,1900]" box="[151,1435,949,972]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyLead box="[151,1435,949,972]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">2 Entirely pallid, cream to tan on head and mesosoma .................................................................................................. 3</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,885,1900]" box="[151,1436,981,1004]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,981,1004]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">- Dark brown above antennal sockets, dark brown markings on mesoscutum, propodeum........................................... 4</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,885,1900]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyLead pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
3 Ocelli greatly enlarged, ocellar diameter nearly 1/3 width of interocular distance at level of median ocellus (
<figureCitation box="[1356,1423,1013,1036]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–20" captionStartId="7.[151,271,1935,1959]" captionTargetBox="[183,1399,198,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-105@7.[169,1413,197,1914]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 1–20. Female heads (1–5), dorsal (6–10) and lateral (11–15) views of male genitalia, and male sternum 8 (16–20) of Perdita (Xerophasma). Perdita celadona (1, 6, 11, 16), P. pallida (2, 7, 12, 17), P. vespertina (3, 8, 13, 18), P. bequaertiana (4, 9, 14, 19), P. rhondae (5, 10, 15, 20). Shaded areas indicate dark markings on female heads." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302216" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302216/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
); large (forewing length&gt; 
<quantity box="[465,528,1045,1068]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" unit="mm" value="7.0">7 mm</quantity>
) .............................................................................................. 
<taxonomicName authority="Cockerell" authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1951" box="[1183,1436,1045,1068]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Perdita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bequaertiana">
<emphasis box="[1183,1325,1045,1068]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">bequaertiana</emphasis>
Cockerell
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,885,1900]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyLead pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
- Ocelli moderately enlarged, ocellar diameter approximately 1/5 width of interocular distance at level of median ocellus (
<figureCitation box="[289,355,1109,1132]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–20" captionStartId="7.[151,271,1935,1959]" captionTargetBox="[183,1399,198,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-105@7.[169,1413,197,1914]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 1–20. Female heads (1–5), dorsal (6–10) and lateral (11–15) views of male genitalia, and male sternum 8 (16–20) of Perdita (Xerophasma). Perdita celadona (1, 6, 11, 16), P. pallida (2, 7, 12, 17), P. vespertina (3, 8, 13, 18), P. bequaertiana (4, 9, 14, 19), P. rhondae (5, 10, 15, 20). Shaded areas indicate dark markings on female heads." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302216" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302216/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
); small (forewing length &lt;
<quantity box="[646,703,1109,1132]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" unit="mm" value="7.0">7mm</quantity>
) ........................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Timberlake" authorityName="Timberlake" authorityYear="1954" box="[1232,1436,1109,1132]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Perdita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallida">
<emphasis box="[1232,1308,1109,1132]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">pallida</emphasis>
Timberlake
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,885,1900]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyLead pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
4 Frons dark throughout (
<figureCitation box="[455,549,1141,1164]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–20" captionStartId="7.[151,271,1935,1959]" captionTargetBox="[183,1399,198,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-105@7.[169,1413,197,1914]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 1–20. Female heads (1–5), dorsal (6–10) and lateral (11–15) views of male genitalia, and male sternum 8 (16–20) of Perdita (Xerophasma). Perdita celadona (1, 6, 11, 16), P. pallida (2, 7, 12, 17), P. vespertina (3, 8, 13, 18), P. bequaertiana (4, 9, 14, 19), P. rhondae (5, 10, 15, 20). Shaded areas indicate dark markings on female heads." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302216" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302216/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Fig. 1, 3</figureCitation>
); gena narrower than eye in lateral view; mesoscutum either dull or densely punctate ................................................................................................................................................................................ 5
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,885,1900]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyLead pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
- Frons with small dark mark above each antennal socket (
<figureCitation box="[807,873,1205,1228]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–20" captionStartId="7.[151,271,1935,1959]" captionTargetBox="[183,1399,198,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-105@7.[169,1413,197,1914]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 1–20. Female heads (1–5), dorsal (6–10) and lateral (11–15) views of male genitalia, and male sternum 8 (16–20) of Perdita (Xerophasma). Perdita celadona (1, 6, 11, 16), P. pallida (2, 7, 12, 17), P. vespertina (3, 8, 13, 18), P. bequaertiana (4, 9, 14, 19), P. rhondae (5, 10, 15, 20). Shaded areas indicate dark markings on female heads." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302216" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302216/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
); gena broader than eye in lateral view; mesoscutum polished and sparsely punctate ......................................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Griswold" authorityName="Griswold" authorityYear="2010" box="[1242,1436,1237,1260]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Perdita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rhondae">
<emphasis box="[1242,1330,1237,1260]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">rhondae</emphasis>
Griswold
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,885,1900]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyLead pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
5 Mandible without preapical tooth (
<figureCitation box="[574,640,1269,1292]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–20" captionStartId="7.[151,271,1935,1959]" captionTargetBox="[183,1399,198,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-105@7.[169,1413,197,1914]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 1–20. Female heads (1–5), dorsal (6–10) and lateral (11–15) views of male genitalia, and male sternum 8 (16–20) of Perdita (Xerophasma). Perdita celadona (1, 6, 11, 16), P. pallida (2, 7, 12, 17), P. vespertina (3, 8, 13, 18), P. bequaertiana (4, 9, 14, 19), P. rhondae (5, 10, 15, 20). Shaded areas indicate dark markings on female heads." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302216" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302216/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
); clypeus entirely cream-colored; mesoscutum golden brown or dark with 'U' shaped yellow marking, surface shiny, rather densely punctate ............................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Griswold &amp; Miller" authorityName="Griswold &amp; Miller" authorityYear="2010" box="[1118,1435,1301,1324]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Perdita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vespertina">
<emphasis box="[1118,1229,1301,1324]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">vespertina</emphasis>
Griswold &amp; Miller
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,885,1900]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyLead pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis box="[151,160,1333,1356]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">-</emphasis>
Mandible with preapical tooth (
<figureCitation box="[536,598,1333,1356]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–20" captionStartId="7.[151,271,1935,1959]" captionTargetBox="[183,1399,198,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-105@7.[169,1413,197,1914]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 1–20. Female heads (1–5), dorsal (6–10) and lateral (11–15) views of male genitalia, and male sternum 8 (16–20) of Perdita (Xerophasma). Perdita celadona (1, 6, 11, 16), P. pallida (2, 7, 12, 17), P. vespertina (3, 8, 13, 18), P. bequaertiana (4, 9, 14, 19), P. rhondae (5, 10, 15, 20). Shaded areas indicate dark markings on female heads." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302216" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302216/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); clypeus with medial dark band; mesoscutum entirely dark, surface dull, very sparsely punctate ............................................................................................................... ce 
<emphasis box="[1155,1229,1365,1388]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">ladona</emphasis>
Griswold &amp; Miller
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,885,1900]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyLead pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
6 Supraclypeal area with conical protuberance and dense tuft of erect, apically bent hair; clypeus densely punctate..... ........................................................................................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Griswold" authorityName="Griswold" authorityYear="2010" box="[1242,1436,1429,1452]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Perdita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rhondae">
<emphasis box="[1242,1330,1429,1452]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">rhondae</emphasis>
Griswold
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,885,1900]" box="[151,1435,1461,1484]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyLead box="[151,1435,1461,1484]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">- Supraclypeal area flat, without tuft of hair; clypeus very impunctate medially .......................................................... 7</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,885,1900]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyLead pageId="3" pageNumber="4">7 Face cream or golden brown above antennal sockets, with little contrast to clypeus and paraocular area; facial fovea distinct, tear-drop shaped, or ellipsoid ......................................................................................................................... 8</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,885,1900]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyLead pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
- Face dark brown or black above antennal sockets, in distinct contrast to yellow clypeus and paraocular area; facial fovea indistinct, slightly oval .......................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Griswold &amp; Miller" authorityName="Griswold &amp; Miller" authorityYear="2010" box="[1132,1435,1589,1612]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Perdita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="celadona">
<emphasis box="[1132,1230,1589,1612]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">celadona</emphasis>
Griswold &amp; Miller
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,885,1900]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyLead pageId="3" pageNumber="4">8 Ocelli not greatly enlarged, 1/5 width of interocular distance at level of median ocellus; frons cream to pale yellow above antennal sockets ................................................................................................................................................ 9</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,885,1900]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyLead pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
- Ocelli large, 1/3 width of interocular distance at level of median ocellus; frons golden brown above antennal sockets .................................................................................................................................................. 
<taxonomicName authority="Cockerell" authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1951" box="[1183,1436,1717,1740]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Perdita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bequaertiana">
<emphasis box="[1183,1325,1717,1740]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">bequaertiana</emphasis>
Cockerell
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,885,1900]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyLead pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
9 Ocelli not bordered by dark lines except sometimes a single fine line medially between two lateral ocelli; prestigma pale in contrast to dark vein R; stigma without dark posterior margin; facial fovea tear-drop shaped ......................... ......................................................................................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Timberlake" authorityName="Timberlake" authorityYear="1954" box="[1232,1436,1813,1836]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Perdita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallida">
<emphasis box="[1232,1308,1813,1836]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">pallida</emphasis>
Timberlake
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,885,1900]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<keyLead pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
- Dark markings present at least anterior to lateral ocelli, often more extensive in ocellar region; prestigma dark, similar to vein R; stigma with dark posterior margin; facial fovea elongate ellipsoid ....... 
<taxonomicName authority="Griswold &amp; Miller" authorityName="Griswold &amp; Miller" authorityYear="2010" box="[1118,1435,1877,1900]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Perdita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vespertina">
<emphasis box="[1118,1229,1877,1900]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">vespertina</emphasis>
Griswold &amp; Miller
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
